      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A zero-pressure accumulation (ZPA) conveyor stops and queues products with controlled gaps between each item, eliminating product-to-product contact and backpressure. Each zone has independent drive control and a sensor to detect product presence. When a downstream zone is occupied, upstream zones hold their products with gaps between them. ZPA prevents product damage, label scuffing, carton crushing, and shifting of contents inside cases."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does zero-pressure accumulation work?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "ZPA conveyors divide the conveyor into zones, each with its own drive mechanism and photo-eye sensor. Zone logic follows a simple rule: if the downstream zone is empty, release and transport; if occupied, stop and hold. This creates a cascading release pattern where products queue with gaps between them. MDR (Motor Driven Roller) conveyors use 24VDC motorized rollers per zone. Belt-driven systems use pneumatic clutches or brakes per zone."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What products require zero-pressure accumulation?",
